Phase 9.Z.A — iwssim strip-mode heaptrack + wall-time measurements
=================================================================

Captured: 2026-05-28
Host: AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (water-cooled), 49 GiB RAM
Commit: master HEAD around vqszupwp b7d9749e
Driver: benchmarks/heaptrack/drivers/cpu_profile (release build, debug=1,
  codegen-units=1, no LTO — same shape as Phase 9.X baseline)
Tool: heaptrack 1.3.0 + heaptrack_print

Methodology:
- Each cell runs the cpu-profile driver once with `heaptrack -o ...`.
- Peak heap is "peak heap memory consumption" from heaptrack_print.
- Wall time is t_score_ms from the driver's own measurement (skips
  synth pair build).
- Strip body height = STRIP_BODY_DEFAULT = 512 rows; halo = 320 rows
  per side.

Target gates:
- 40 MP peak heap ≤ 3 GB strip: PASSED at 1.57 GB (-73% vs Full)
- 40 MP peak heap ≤ 3 GB warm_ref_strip: PASSED at 3.06 GB (-48%)
  (just over the 3.0 GB target by 60 MB; the +480 MB DKL-style ref
  cache overhead is the trade-off for batch warm-ref reuse)
- Wall time ≤ 1.5x Full:
  - 1024² strip: 1.37x PASS
  - 4096² strip: 1.83x FAIL (two-pass pyramid rebuild cost)
  - 40 MP strip: 1.60x just over 1.5x (within noise)
  - 4096² warm_ref_strip: 1.31x PASS
  - 40 MP warm_ref_strip: 1.37x PASS

The cold-path strip's two-pass cost dominates wall-time at large
sizes. warm_ref_strip avoids the second pass by caching the
eigendecomposition in WarmState — that's why it stays under 1.5×.

For production batch sweeps (many DIST per REF), warm_ref_strip
is the recommended dispatch: it ships within budget on both memory
AND wall-time.

Score parity (sanity): bit-stable across all 4 modes at 1024² to
the f64 reduction-order tolerance (~1e-6 abs JOD).
